WEBVTT

00:22.000 --> 00:23.200
CHAPTER IV.

00:23.600 --> 00:29.300
That which rules within, when it is according to Nature, is so affected with respect to

00:29.300 --> 00:35.300
the events which happen that it always easily adapts itself to that which is possible and

00:35.300 --> 00:41.120
is presented to it, for it requires no definite material, but it moves towards its purpose

00:41.120 --> 00:47.000
under certain conditions however, and it makes a material for itself out of that which opposes

00:47.000 --> 00:53.880
it as fire lays hold of what falls into it, but which a small light would have been extinguished.

00:53.880 --> 00:59.880
But when the fire is strong, it soon appropriates to itself the matter which is heaped on it,

00:59.940 --> 01:06.860
and consumes it, and rises higher by means of this very material. Let no act be done

01:06.860 --> 01:14.040
without a purpose, nor otherwise than according to the perfect principles of art. Men seek

01:14.040 --> 01:19.220
retreats for themselves, houses in the country, seashores, and the mountains,

01:19.800 --> 01:26.220
and thou too art wont to desire such things very much. But this is altogether a mark of the most

01:26.220 --> 01:33.220
common sort of men. For it is in thy power whenever thou shalt choose to retire into thyself. For

01:33.220 --> 01:39.020
nowhere, either with more quiet or more freedom from trouble, does a man retire than into his

01:39.020 --> 01:45.340
own soul, particularly when he has within him such thoughts that by looking into them he is

01:45.340 --> 01:50.500
immediately in perfect tranquillity. And I affirm that tranquillity is nothing else than the good

01:50.500 --> 01:56.420
ordering of the mind. Constantly, then, give to thyself this retreat, and renew thyself,

01:57.280 --> 02:03.120
and let thy principles be brief and fundamental, which, as soon as thou shalt recur to them,

02:03.620 --> 02:09.440
will be sufficient to cleanse the soul completely, and to send thee back free from all discontent

02:09.440 --> 02:17.280
with the things to which thou returnest. For with what art thou discontented? With the badness of

02:17.280 --> 02:24.320
men? Recall to thy mind this conclusion, that rational animals exist for one another, and that

02:24.320 --> 02:31.600
to endure is a part of justice, and that men do wrong involuntarily. And consider how many already,

02:31.600 --> 02:38.100
after mutual enmity, suspicion, hatred, and fighting, have been stretched dead,

02:38.660 --> 02:46.940
reduced to ashes, and be quiet at last. But perhaps thou art dissatisfied with that which

02:46.940 --> 02:53.780
is assigned to thee out of the universe. Recall to thy recollection this alternative. Either

02:53.780 --> 03:01.100
there is providence or atoms, fortuitous concurrence of things, or remember the arguments by which it

03:01.100 --> 03:07.780
has been proved that the world is a kind of political community, and be quiet at last. But

03:07.780 --> 03:14.880
perhaps corporeal things will still fasten upon thee. Consider then further that the mind mingles

03:14.880 --> 03:20.980
not with the breath, whether moving gently or violently, when it has once drawn itself apart,

03:21.180 --> 03:27.520
and discovered its own power. And think also of all that thou hast heard and assented to about

03:27.520 --> 03:34.400
pain and pleasure, and be quiet at last. But perhaps the desire of the thing called fame

03:34.400 --> 03:41.080
will torment thee. See how soon everything is forgotten, and look at the chaos of infinite

03:41.080 --> 03:48.140
time on each side of the present, and the emptiness of applause, and the changeableness and want of

03:48.140 --> 03:57.500
judgment in those who pretend to give praise, and the narrowness of the space within which it is

03:57.500 --> 04:04.260
for the whole earth is a point, and how small a nook in it is this thy dwelling place, and how

04:04.260 --> 04:11.180
few are there in it, and what kind of people are they who will praise thee. This then remains.

04:12.020 --> 04:19.880
Remember to retire into this little territory of thy own, and above all do not distract or strain

04:19.880 --> 04:30.160
thyself, but be free at look and things as a man, as a human being, as a citizen, as a mortal.

04:31.140 --> 04:37.520
But among the things readiest to thy hand to which thou shalt return, let there be these which are

04:37.520 --> 04:44.200
two. One is that things do not touch the soul, for they are external and remain immovable,

04:44.200 --> 04:50.600
but our perturbations come only from the opinion which is within. The other is that all these

04:50.600 --> 04:57.420
things which thou seest change immediately and will no longer be, and constantly bear in mind

04:57.420 --> 05:03.160
how many of these changes thou hast already witnessed. The universe is transformation,

05:03.880 --> 05:12.700
life is opinion. If our intellectual part is common, the reason also, in respect of which

05:12.700 --> 05:19.780
we are rational beings, is common. If this is so, common also is the reason which commands us what

05:19.780 --> 05:28.100
to do and what not to do. If this is so, there is a common law also. If this is so, we are fellow

05:28.100 --> 05:36.160
citizens. If this is so, we are members of some political community. If this is so, the world is

05:36.160 --> 05:42.440
in a manner, a state. For of what other common political community will anyone say that the whole

05:42.440 --> 05:49.100
human race are members. And from thence, from this common political community comes also our

05:49.100 --> 05:56.040
very intellectual faculty and reasoning faculty and our capacity for law, or whence do they come.

05:56.780 --> 06:03.060
For as my earthly part is a portion given to me from certain earth, and that which is watery from

06:03.060 --> 06:09.160
another element, and that which is hot and fiery from some peculiar source, for nothing comes out

06:09.160 --> 06:15.680
of that which is nothing, as nothing also returns to nonexistence. So also the intellectual part

06:15.680 --> 06:23.340
comes from some source. Death is such as generation is, a mystery of nature, a composition out of the

06:23.340 --> 06:30.000
same elements and a decomposition into the same, and altogether not a thing of which any man should

06:30.000 --> 06:37.340
be ashamed. For it is not contrary to the nature of a reasonable animal, and not contrary to the

06:37.340 --> 06:45.720
reason of our constitution. It is natural that these things should be done by such persons. It is

06:45.720 --> 06:52.180
a matter of necessity, and if a man will not have it so, he will not allow the fig tree to have juice.

06:53.360 --> 07:00.500
But by all means bear this in mind, that within a very short time both thou and he will be dead,

07:00.500 --> 07:08.160
and soon not even your names will be left behind. Take away thy opinion, and then there is taken

07:08.160 --> 07:14.300
away the complaint I have been harmed. Take away the complaint I have been harmed, and the harm is

07:14.300 --> 07:21.700
taken away. That which does not make a man worse than he was, also does not make his life worse,

07:22.760 --> 07:30.120
nor does it harm him either from without or from within. The nature of that which is universally

07:30.120 --> 07:38.600
useful has been compelled to do this. Consider that everything which happens, happens justly,

07:39.000 --> 07:45.860
and if thou observest carefully, thou wilt find it to be so. I do not say only with respect to the

07:45.860 --> 07:51.940
continuity of the series of things, but with respect to what is just, and as if it were done

07:51.940 --> 07:58.420
by one who assigns to each thing its value. Observe then that thou hast begun, and whatever

07:58.420 --> 08:04.960
thou doest, do it in conjunction with this, the being good, and in the sense in which a man is

08:04.960 --> 08:11.960
properly understood to be good. Keep to this in every action. Do not have such an opinion of things

08:11.960 --> 08:19.420
as he has who does thee wrong, or such as he wishes thee to have, but look at them as they are in truth.

08:20.800 --> 08:26.600
A man should always have these two rules in readiness, the one to do only whatever the reason

08:26.600 --> 08:33.660
of the ruling and legislating faculty may suggest for the use of men, the other to change thy opinion,

08:34.160 --> 08:39.800
if there is anyone at hand who sets thee right and moves thee from any opinion. But this change

08:39.800 --> 08:45.120
of opinion must proceed only from a certain persuasion, as of what is just or of common

08:45.120 --> 08:52.820
advantage and the like, not because it appears pleasant or brings reputation. Hast thou reason?

08:52.820 --> 09:01.440
I have. Why then dost not thou use it? For if this does its own work, what else dost thou wish?

09:02.620 --> 09:07.560
Thou hast existed as a part. Thou shalt disappear in that which produced thee,

09:07.720 --> 09:13.060
but rather thou shalt be received back into its seminal principle by transmutation.

09:14.700 --> 09:22.240
Many grains of frankincense on the same altar. One falls before, another falls after. But it

09:22.240 --> 09:30.300
makes no difference. Within ten days thou wilt seem a god to those to whom thou art now a beast

09:30.300 --> 09:38.120
and an ape, if thou wilt return to thy principles and to worship of reason. Do not act as if thou

09:38.120 --> 09:45.720
wert going to live ten thousand years. Death hangs over thee. While thou livest, while it is in thy

09:45.720 --> 09:53.860
power, be good. How much trouble he avoids who does not look to see what his neighbor says or

09:53.860 --> 10:01.540
does or thinks, but only to what he does himself, that it may be just and pure. Or, as Agathon says,

10:02.120 --> 10:08.220
look not round at the depraved morals of others, but run straight along the line without deviating

10:08.220 --> 10:14.920
from it. He who has a vehement desire for posthumous fame does not consider that every one of those who

10:14.920 --> 10:21.420
remember him will himself also die very soon. Then again also they who have succeeded them,

10:21.840 --> 10:25.940
until the whole remembrance shall have been extinguished as it is transmitted through men

10:25.940 --> 10:32.480
who foolishly admire and perish. Suppose that those who will remember are even immortal,

10:32.940 --> 10:39.000
and that the remembrance will be immortal. What then is this to thee? And I say not what is it

10:39.000 --> 10:45.440
to the dead, but what is it to the living? What is praise, except indeed so far as it has a certain

10:45.440 --> 10:53.940
utility? For thou now rejectest unseasonably the gift of nature, clinging to something else.

10:54.440 --> 11:00.440
Everything which is in any way beautiful is beautiful in itself, and terminates in itself,

11:00.860 --> 11:07.180
not having praise as a part of itself. Neither worse than nor better is a thing made by being

11:07.180 --> 11:13.400
praised. I affirm this also of the things which are called beautiful by the vulgar, for example,

11:13.680 --> 11:18.740
material things and works of art. That which is really beautiful has no need of anything,

11:19.520 --> 11:26.300
not more than law, not more than truth, not more than benevolence or modesty. Which of these things

11:26.300 --> 11:33.020
is beautiful because it is praised, or spoiled by being blamed? Is such a thing as an emerald

11:33.020 --> 11:40.460
made worse than it was, if it is not praised? Or gold, ivory, purple, a lyre, a little knife,

11:40.520 --> 11:48.600
a flower, a shrub? If souls continue to exist, how does the air contain them from eternity? But how

11:48.600 --> 11:54.080
does the earth contain the bodies of those who have been buried from time so remote? For as here

11:54.080 --> 11:59.600
the mutation of these bodies, after a certain continuance, whatever it may be, and their

11:59.600 --> 12:05.120
solution make room for other dead bodies. So the souls which are removed into the air after

12:05.120 --> 12:11.020
subsisting for some time are transmuted and diffuse, and assume a fiery nature by being

12:11.020 --> 12:16.940
received into the seminal intelligence of the universe. And in this way make room for the fresh

12:16.940 --> 12:22.700
souls which come to dwell there. And this is the answer which a man might give on the hypothesis

12:22.700 --> 12:28.240
of souls continuing to exist. But we must not only think of the number of bodies which are thus

12:28.240 --> 12:35.480
buried, but also of the number of animals which are daily eaten by us and the other animals. For

12:35.480 --> 12:41.080
what a number is consumed, and thus in a manner buried in the bodies of those who feed on them,

12:41.480 --> 12:47.960
and nevertheless this earth receives them by reason of the changes of these bodies into blood,

12:48.640 --> 12:55.580
and the transformations into the aerial or the fiery element. What is the investigation into the

12:55.580 --> 13:01.560
length of the matter? The division into that which is material, and that which is the cause

13:01.560 --> 13:08.640
of form, the formal. Do not be whirled about, but in every movement have respect to justice,

13:09.080 --> 13:14.940
and on the occasion of every impression maintain the faculty of comprehension or understanding.

13:16.040 --> 13:22.820
Everything harmonizes with me which is harmonious to thee, O universe. Nothing for me is too early

13:22.820 --> 13:28.620
nor too late which is in due time for thee. Everything is fruit to me which thy seasons

13:28.620 --> 13:36.120
bring, O nature. From thee are all things, in thee are all things, to thee all things return.

13:37.120 --> 13:46.340
The poet says, Dear city of sea-crops, and wilt not thou say, Dear city of Zeus. Occupy thyself

13:46.340 --> 13:52.740
with few things, says the philosopher, if thou wouldst be tranquil. But consider if it would not

13:52.740 --> 13:58.280
be better to say, Do what is necessary, and whatever the reason of the animal which is

13:58.280 --> 14:04.440
naturally social requires, and as it requires. For this brings not only the tranquility which

14:04.440 --> 14:10.540
comes from doing well, but also that which comes from doing few things. For the greatest part of

14:10.540 --> 14:16.680
what we say and do being unnecessary, if a man takes this away, he will have more leisure and

14:16.680 --> 14:23.040
less uneasiness. Accordingly, on every occasion a man should ask himself, Is this one of the

14:23.040 --> 14:29.260
unnecessary things? Now a man should take away not only unnecessary acts but also unnecessary

14:29.260 --> 14:36.680
thoughts, for thus superfluous acts will not follow after. Try how the life of a good man

14:36.680 --> 14:43.160
suits thee, the life of him who is satisfied with his portion out of the whole and satisfied

14:43.160 --> 14:51.700
with his own just acts and benevolent disposition. Hast thou seen those things? Look also at these.

14:52.120 --> 15:00.060
Do not disturb thyself. Make thyself all simplicity. Does anyone do wrong? It is to himself that he

15:00.060 --> 15:07.440
does wrong. Has anything happened to thee? Well, out of the universe from the beginning, everything

15:07.440 --> 15:15.000
which happens has been apportioned and spun out to thee. In a word, thy life is short. Thou must

15:15.000 --> 15:23.620
turn to profit the present by the aid of reason and justice. Be sober in thy relaxation. Are there

15:23.620 --> 15:30.600
it is a well-arranged universe or a chaos huddled together, but still a universe? But can a certain

15:30.600 --> 15:37.960
order subsist in thee and disorder in all? And this, too, when all things are so separated and

15:37.960 --> 15:47.060
diffused and sympathetic. A black character, a womanish character, a stubborn character, bestial,

15:47.500 --> 15:57.360
childish, annual, stupid, counterfeit, scurrilous, fraudulent, tyrannical. If he is a stranger to the

15:57.360 --> 16:02.640
universe who does not know what is in it, no less is he a stranger who does not know what is going

16:02.640 --> 16:10.920
on in it. He is a runaway who flies from social reason. He is blind who shuts the eyes of the

16:10.920 --> 16:16.680
understanding. He is poor who has need of another and has not from himself all things which are

16:16.680 --> 16:23.540
useful for life. He is an abscess on the universe who withdraws and separates himself from the reason

16:23.540 --> 16:28.820
of our common nature through being displeased with the things which happen. For the same nature

16:28.820 --> 16:35.360
produces this and has produced thee, too. He is a piece rent asunder from the state who tears his

16:35.360 --> 16:43.080
own soul from that of reasonable animals, which is one. The one is a philosopher without a tunic,

16:43.380 --> 16:50.320
and the other without a book. Here is another half-naked. Bread I have not, he says, and I

16:50.320 --> 16:58.420
reason, and I do not get the means of living out of my learning, and I abide by my reason.

17:00.020 --> 17:06.220
Love the art, poor as it may be, which thou hast learned, and be content with it, and pass

17:06.220 --> 17:12.280
through the rest of life like one who has entrusted to the gods with his whole soul all that he has,

17:12.280 --> 17:21.220
making himself neither the tyrant nor the slave of any man. Consider, for example, the times of

17:21.220 --> 17:27.660
Vespasian. Thou wilt see all these things, people marrying, bringing up children, sick, dying,

17:28.060 --> 17:34.400
warring, feasting, trafficking, cultivating the ground, flattering, obstinately arrogant, suspecting,

17:34.520 --> 17:39.700
plotting, wishing for some to die, grumbling about the present, loving, heaping up treasure,

17:39.700 --> 17:46.560
desiring consulship, kingly power. Well, then, that life of these people no longer exists at all.

17:47.420 --> 17:54.540
Again, removed to the time of Trajan, again all is the same. Their life, too, is gone. In like

17:54.540 --> 18:00.900
manner, view also the other epics of time and of whole nations, and see how many, after great

18:00.900 --> 18:07.000
efforts, soon fell and were resolved into the elements. But chiefly thou shouldst think of

18:07.000 --> 18:12.920
those whom thou hast thyself known distracting themselves about idle things, neglecting to do

18:12.920 --> 18:17.600
what was in accordance with their proper constitution, and to hold firmly to this,

18:17.700 --> 18:23.380
and to be content with it. And herein it is necessary to remember that the attention given

18:23.380 --> 18:30.700
to everything has its proper value and proportion. For thus thou wilt not be dissatisfied if thou

18:30.700 --> 18:37.040
applies thyself to smaller matters no further than is fit. The words which were formerly familiar

18:37.040 --> 18:44.340
are now antiquated. So also the names of those who were famed of old are now in a manner antiquated.

18:44.780 --> 18:52.140
Camillus, Caeso, Volasus, Leonidas, and a little after also Scipio and Cato, then Augustus, then

18:52.140 --> 18:59.100
also Hadrianus and Antoninus. For all things soon pass away and become a mere tale. In complete

18:59.100 --> 19:06.300
oblivion soon buries them. And I say this of those who have shown in a wondrous way. For the rest,

19:06.900 --> 19:12.420
as soon as they have breathed out their breath, they are gone and no man speaks of them. And to

19:12.420 --> 19:20.660
conclude the matter, what is even an eternal remembrance? A mere nothing. What then is that

19:20.660 --> 19:27.740
about which we ought to employ our serious pains? This one thing, thoughts just and acts social,

19:27.740 --> 19:34.080
and words which never lie, and a disposition which gladly accepts all that happens as necessary,

19:34.580 --> 19:44.220
as usual, as flowing from a principle and a source of the same kind. Willingly give thyself up to

19:44.220 --> 19:50.520
Clotho, one of the fates, allowing her to spin thy thread into whatever things she pleases.

19:52.280 --> 19:57.500
Everything is only for a day, both that which remembers and that which is remembered.

19:59.660 --> 20:04.840
Observe constantly that all things take place by change, and accustom thyself to consider that

20:04.840 --> 20:10.180
the nature of the universe loves nothing so much as to change the things which are, and to make

20:10.180 --> 20:16.480
new things like them. For everything that exists is in a manner the seed of that which will be,

20:16.480 --> 20:22.520
but thou art thinking only of seeds which are cast into the earth or into a womb. But this is a

20:22.520 --> 20:29.920
very vulgar notion. Thou wilt soon die, and thou art not yet simple, not free from perturbations,

20:30.300 --> 20:36.640
not without suspicion of being hurt by external things, nor kindly disposed toward all. Nor dost

20:36.640 --> 20:45.060
thou yet place wisdom only in acting justly. Examine men's ruling principles, even those of

20:45.060 --> 20:53.300
wise, what kind of things they avoid and what kind they pursue. What is evil to thee does not subsist

20:53.300 --> 20:59.540
in the ruling principle of another, nor yet in any turning and mutation of thy corporeal covering.

21:00.840 --> 21:06.920
Where is it then? It is in that part of thee in which subsists the power of forming opinions

21:06.920 --> 21:14.820
about evils. Let this power then not form such opinions, and all as well. And if that which is

21:14.820 --> 21:22.520
nearest to it, the poor body, is cut, burnt, filled with matter and rottenness, nevertheless,

21:23.020 --> 21:28.620
let the part which forms opinions about these things be quiet. That is, let it judge that

21:28.620 --> 21:34.480
nothing is either bad or good which can happen equally to the bad man and the good. For that

21:34.480 --> 21:40.440
which happens equally to him who lives contrary to nature, and to him who lives according to nature,

21:40.440 --> 21:47.980
is neither according to nature nor contrary to nature. Constantly regard the universe as one

21:47.980 --> 21:55.080
living being, having one substance and one soul, and observe how all things have reference to one

21:55.080 --> 22:01.480
perception, the perception of this one living being, and how all things act with one movement,

22:02.280 --> 22:08.580
and how all things are the cooperative causes of all things which exist. Observe, too, the continuous

22:08.580 --> 22:16.500
spinning of the thread and the contextual of the web. Thou art a little soul bearing about a corpse,

22:17.080 --> 22:23.320
as Epictetus used to say. It is no evil for things to undergo change, and no good for things to

22:23.320 --> 22:29.880
subsist in consequence of change. Time is like a river made up of the events which happened,

22:30.340 --> 22:36.600
and a violent stream. For as soon as a thing has been seen, it is carried away, and another comes

22:36.600 --> 22:44.220
in its place, and this will be carried away, too. Everything which happens is as familiar and well

22:44.220 --> 22:50.340
known as the rose in spring and the fruit in summer. For such is disease, and death, and calumny,

22:50.540 --> 22:56.800
and treachery, and whatever else delights fools or vexes them. In the series of things, those

22:56.800 --> 23:02.620
which follow are always aptly fitted to those which have gone before. For this series is not

23:02.620 --> 23:09.460
a mere enumeration of disjointed things, which only has a necessary sequence, but it is a rational

23:09.460 --> 23:16.460
connection, and as all existing things are arranged together harmoniously, so the things which come

23:16.460 --> 23:23.120
into existence exhibit no mere succession but a certain wonderful relationship. Always remember

23:23.120 --> 23:32.480
the saying of Heraclitus that the death of earth is to become water, and the death of water is to

23:32.480 --> 23:39.600
become fire, and reversely. And think too of him who forgets whither the way leads, and that men

23:39.600 --> 23:44.820
quarrel with that with which they are most constantly in communion, the reason which

23:44.820 --> 23:50.700
governs the universe. And the things which they daily meet with seem to them strange,

23:51.340 --> 23:57.000
and consider that we ought not to act and speak as if we were asleep, for even in sleep we seem

23:57.000 --> 24:03.860
to act and speak, and that we ought not, like children who learn from their parents, simply to

24:03.860 --> 24:12.120
act and speak as we have been taught. If any God told thee that thou shalt die tomorrow, or certainly

24:12.120 --> 24:17.980
on the day after tomorrow, thou wouldst not care much whether it was on the third day or on the

24:18.520 --> 24:23.440
morrow, unless thou wast in the highest degree mean-spirited, for how small is the difference.

24:23.440 --> 24:30.760
So think, it is no great thing to die after as many years as thou canst name rather than tomorrow.

24:31.820 --> 24:36.940
Think continually how many physicians are dead after often contracting their eyebrows over the

24:36.940 --> 24:42.680
sick, and how many astrologers after predicting with great pretensions the deaths of others,

24:43.200 --> 24:50.000
and how many philosophers after endless discourses on death or immortality, how many heroes after

24:51.220 --> 24:56.580
and how many tyrants who have used their power over men's lives with terrible insolence as if

24:56.580 --> 25:03.780
they were immortal, and how many cities are entirely dead, so to speak, Helis and Pompeii

25:03.780 --> 25:11.620
and Herculaneum, and others innumerable. Add to the reckoning all whom thou hast known, one after

25:11.620 --> 25:18.240
another. One man, after burying another, has been laid out dead, and another buries him,

25:18.240 --> 25:25.960
and all this in a short time. To conclude, always observe how ephemeral and worthless human things

25:25.960 --> 25:32.780
are, and what was yesterday a little mucus, tomorrow will be a mummy or ashes. Pass then

25:32.780 --> 25:39.580
through this little space of time conformably to nature, and end thy journey in content, just as

25:39.580 --> 25:45.320
an olive falls off when it is ripe, blessing nature who produced it, and thanking the tree

25:45.320 --> 25:52.280
on which it grew. Be like the promontory against which the waves continually break,

25:52.780 --> 25:59.760
but it stands firm and tames the fury of the water around it. Unhappy am I, because this has

25:59.760 --> 26:06.840
happened to me. Not so. But happy am I, though this has happened to me, because I continue free

26:06.840 --> 26:13.140
from pain, neither crushed by the present nor fearing the future. For such a thing as this might

26:13.140 --> 26:18.300
have happened to every man, but every man would not have continued free from pain on such an

26:18.300 --> 26:25.960
occasion. Why, then, is that rather a misfortune than this a good fortune? And dost thou in all

26:25.960 --> 26:33.080
cases call that a man's misfortune, which is not a deviation from man's nature? And does a thing

26:33.080 --> 26:38.200
seem to thee to be a deviation from man's nature, when it is not contrary to the will of man's

26:38.200 --> 26:45.920
nature? Well, thou knowest the will of nature. Will then this which has happened prevent thee

26:45.920 --> 26:52.700
from being just, magnanimous, temperate, prudent, secure against inconsiderate opinions and

26:52.700 --> 26:58.600
falsehoods? Will it prevent thee from having modesty, freedom, and everything else, by the

26:58.600 --> 27:06.180
presence of which man's nature obtains all that is its own? Remember, too, in every occasion which

27:06.180 --> 27:13.100
leads thee to vexation to apply this principle, not that this is a misfortune, but that to bear

27:13.100 --> 27:20.260
it nobly is good fortune. It is a vulgar but still a useful help towards contempt of death to pass

27:20.260 --> 27:26.880
and review those who have tenaciously stuck to life. What more, then, have they gained than those

27:26.880 --> 27:34.620
who have died early? Certainly they lie in their tomb somewhere at last. Cadicianus, Fabius,

27:34.620 --> 27:40.720
Julianus, Lepidus, or anyone else like them, who have carried out many to be buried, and then were

27:40.720 --> 27:47.600
carried out themselves. Altogether the interval is small between birth and death. And consider,

27:47.880 --> 27:53.420
with how much trouble, and in company with what sort of people, and in what a feeble body this

27:53.420 --> 28:00.190
interval is laboriously passed, do not then consider life a thing of any value. For look to the

28:00.790 --> 28:07.630
behind thee, and to the time which is before thee, another boundless space. In this infinity, then,

28:07.630 --> 28:12.170
what is the difference between him who lives three days and him who lives three generations?

28:13.090 --> 28:20.270
Always run the short way. And the short way is the natural. Accordingly say and do everything in

28:20.270 --> 28:26.270
conformity with the soundest reason. For such a purpose frees a man from trouble and warfare,

28:26.270 --> 28:30.430
and all artifice, and ostentatious this way.

